Clothing Detection Project¶

By: Devanshi Joshi & Samiksha Rajpal

Our project's main objective is to use computer vision algorithms to effectively and precisely identify different clothing items within photographs. Using neural network models, clothing items are be identified, categorized, and analyzed.

Spliting the data into train, test and valid datasets¶

In [2]:
dataset_path = pathlib.Path('datasets')
train_ratio = 0.7
valid_ratio = 0.2

for category in ['train', 'valid', 'test']:
    os.makedirs(dataset_path / category, exist_ok=True)

def split_data(class_name):
    class_path = dataset_path / class_name
    images = os.listdir(class_path)
    random.shuffle(images)

    train_size = int(len(images) * train_ratio)
    valid_size = int(len(images) * valid_ratio)

    for i, image in enumerate(images):
        if i < train_size:
            target_folder = 'train'
        elif i < train_size + valid_size:
            target_folder = 'valid'
        else:
            target_folder = 'test'

        target_path = dataset_path / target_folder / class_name
        os.makedirs(target_path, exist_ok=True)
        try:
            shutil.copy(class_path / image, target_path / image)
        except PermissionError:
            print(f"Permission denied for {image}. Skipping...")

# Apply the split function to each class folder
for class_name in os.listdir(dataset_path):
    if os.path.isdir(dataset_path / class_name):
        split_data(class_name)

print("Data split into train, valid, and test folders.")

Loading the data¶

In [3]:
data_folder = pathlib.Path('datasets')

train_dataset = image_dataset_from_directory(
    data_folder / "train",
    image_size=(180, 180),
    batch_size=32, 
    label_mode='categorical')
validation_dataset = image_dataset_from_directory(
    data_folder / "valid",
    image_size=(180, 180),
    batch_size=32,
        label_mode='categorical')
test_dataset = image_dataset_from_directory(
    data_folder / "test",
    image_size=(180, 180),
    batch_size=32,
        label_mode='categorical')

Looking at some of the images from the dataset¶

In [4]:
def show_batch(image_batch, label_batch, class_names):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
    for n in range(9):
        ax = plt.subplot(3, 3, n + 1)
        plt.imshow(image_batch[n].numpy().astype("uint8"))
        label_index = np.argmax(label_batch[n])
        plt.title(class_names[label_index])
        plt.axis("off")

# Assuming `train_dataset` is your dataset
class_names = train_dataset.class_names

image_batch, label_batch = next(iter(train_dataset))
show_batch(image_batch, label_batch, class_names)

Based on the above images we can observe that some images do not include any model or any person and some images do. These type of different images provide a better training for the model to learn the dimensions and pixels of the clothing in different angles, with and without a model/person.

Data Augmentation¶

In [8]:
data_augmentation = keras.Sequential(
    [
        layers.RandomFlip("horizontal"),
        layers.RandomRotation(0.1),
        layers.RandomBrightness(0.3),
        layers.RandomContrast(0.1)
    ]
)

Looking at the augmented images¶

In [9]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
for images, _ in train_dataset.take(1):
    for i in range(9):
        augmented_images = data_augmentation(images)  
        ax = plt.subplot(3, 3, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(augmented_images[0].numpy().astype("uint8"))
        plt.axis("off")

Here, from the above image we can observe that if we decrease the image brightness than the color of a particular clothing item may change. The color of the item in the above case is green but due to the augmentation step for brightness and contrast the augmented image seems somewhat black. This can be seen as a test case for the model to predict the color and category of cloth.

Applying the model by implementing the vgg16 along with the head layers¶

VGG16 Model-1¶

In [32]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))
x = data_augmentation(inputs)
x = keras.applications.vgg16.preprocess_input(x)
x = conv_base(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
x = layers.Dense(512, activation='relu')(x) # Layer-1 with 512 neurons and relu as the activation function
x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(17, activation='softmax')(x) # Classification for 17 classes
model = keras.Model(inputs, outputs)

model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

import numpy as np
from tensorflow.keras.utils import to_categorical

y_pred = []
y_true = []

for image_batch, label_batch in test_dataset:
    preds = model.predict(image_batch)
    y_pred.extend(np.argmax(preds, axis=1))
    y_true.extend(np.argmax(label_batch.numpy(), axis=1))

y_pred = np.array(y_pred)
y_true = np.array(y_true)

With a test accuracy of 85.43% across 17 classes, the model performed quite well overall.

  • High Performance: Several classes demonstrated exceptional precision and recall, indicating accurate and dependable forecasts for these categories. These classes include class_5, class_8, class_10, class_11, class_13, and class_15.
  • Moderate Performance: Recall and precision for a few classes (class 0 through class 16) ranged from moderate to high, indicating good but marginally less consistent performance.
  • Difficulties in Particular Classes: A few classes—class_6 and class_9, in particular—had good precision but noticeably poorer recall, suggesting that the model tended to overlook pertinent cases in these categories.

In conclusion, the model is doing well across all categories, with some notable exceptions. To improve overall performance, there are, nevertheless, areas for improvement in a few particular classes.

Test accuracy: 4.99%
  • Low Accuracy: With a test accuracy of 4.99%, which is extremely low, the model is clearly not doing a good job of correctly classifying the test data. This degree of accuracy indicates that, as it is, the model is not much better than haphazard guesswork.
  • Problems with Calculating Precision and Recall: When the model is unable to accurately forecast positive cases for one or more classes, the precision and recall calculation is often divided by zero error. This may occur if the model predicts a class consisting of all test samples or if it predicts no classes at all.
  • Imbalance in Score: This problem, together with the low accuracy, may indicate that there is a notable underrepresentation of certain classes in the dataset.

Changing the learning rate as the epochs progress¶

In [20]:
def lr_schedule(epoch):
    lr = 1e-3
    if epoch > 10:
        lr *= 0.5e-3
    elif epoch > 5:
        lr *= 1e-3
    elif epoch > 2:
        lr *= 1e-2
    return lr

lr_scheduler = keras.callbacks.LearningRateScheduler(lr_schedule)

model2.compile(optimizer=keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=1e-3),
              loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])
In [21]:

ResNet50 Model¶

In [28]:
def build_resnet_model(input_shape, num_classes):
    base_model = ResNet50(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=input_shape)
    base_model.trainable = False

    inputs = tf.keras.Input(shape=input_shape)
    x = data_augmentation(inputs)
    x = base_model(x, training=False)
    x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)
    x = layers.Dense(1024, activation='relu')(x)
    x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
    outputs = layers.Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')(x)

    model = models.Model(inputs, outputs)
    return model

model3 = build_resnet_model((180, 180, 3), 17)

Challenges¶

Strategies to Overcome the Challenges:¶

  • Advanced Data Augmentation: Assist the model in learning to distinguish minute distinctions between classes, apply more complex data augmentation techniques that include variances in the images. Methods like shifting, flipping, zooming, and random rotations can work well.
  • Efficient Use of Transfer Learning: Selecting pre-trained models for feature extraction from vast and varied datasets (such as ImageNet) is known as model selection. Using our dataset, we fine-tune the header layers of these pre-trained models to capture the subtleties of clothing items.
  • Optimization Techniques: Adaptive learning rate strategies are used in learning rate scheduling to expedite training and enhance convergence. Batch Normalisation was used to stabilise and expedite training.
  • Using GPUs to expedite data processing and train models.
  • Subtle variations and inter-class variability:
    • Data Visualisation: This stage ensures that the pretreatment and data augmentation stages are correctly set up and aids in comprehending variability.
    • Transfer Learning: By using VGG16 that has already been pre-trained on ImageNet, the model is better able to capture intricate features that may be necessary for differentiating minute changes.

Model Selection¶

  • Accuracy: With an accuracy of 93.25% compared to the VGG16 models' about 85%, ResNet50 performs noticeably better than both of them.

  • F1-Score, Accuracy, and Recall:

    • Once more, ResNet50 performs better than other models with the highest F1-score, recall, and precision. This shows that it can accurately identify classes (precision) and detect the majority of positive samples (recall), which results in an F1-score that is balanced.
    • In terms of precision, recall, and F1-score, VGG16 Model 1 performs somewhat better than Model 2. This could suggest that Model 2's extra dense layer has no effect on performance in this specific test.

  • Model Choice:

With the highest F1-score and a balance between precision and recall, ResNet50 seems to be the best option for this classification task based on the results. The selection between the two VGG16 models may be contingent upon particular needs. If a more straightforward model with fewer parameters is needed, Model 1 may be superior due to its marginally higher macro-average performance.

Why ResNet50 outperforms the VGG16 Models¶

  • The Residual Learning Architecture (ResNet) enables layers to learn from input residuals by introducing skip connections. Because of this, ResNet is far more successful at learning deep features and is easier to train than deep networks like VGG16, which frequently suffer from the vanishing gradient problem.
  • Effective Depth Management: ResNet50 is more effective than VGG16, even though it is deeper (50 layers as opposed to 16). By reducing the amount of parameters through the use of global average pooling, it avoids the computational burden associated with the fully connected layers of VGG16.
  • Improved Feature Learning: ResNet50's depth and design allow it to learn abstract and more complicated features, which is important for applications that call for subtle pattern recognition, including identifying complex clothing styles.
  • Faster Convergence: Compared to VGG16's slower and more gradient-sensitive training procedure, ResNet's skip connections enable efficient backpropagation of gradients, resulting in faster and more stable convergence during training.
  • Better Generalization: ResNet50's ability to construct intricate feature hierarchies makes it more adaptable for a wide range of applications, and it generally exhibits better generalization to a variety of datasets and workloads.
  • Adaptability and Modification Ease: ResNet50's architecture facilitates more adaptable changes and layer additions without substantially impacting its fundamental operations, providing increased flexibility to task-specific alterations.
